I"Ž<p>One can often find similar code in the wild:</p>

<div class="language-ruby highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="n">some_hash</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="nf">has_key?</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">some_key</span><span class="p">)</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">has_something?</code> predicates are not idiomatic in Ruby and
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Hash#has_key?</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Hash#has_value?</code> are nothing, but remnants of the
early days of Ruby. In fact, according to Matz, they are
<a href="http://blade.nagaokaut.ac.jp/cgi-bin/scat.rb/ruby/ruby-core/43765">deprecated</a>
in favor of <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Hash#key?</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Hash#value?</code>.</p>

<p>The above snippet should look like:</p>

<div class="language-ruby highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="n">some_hash</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="nf">key?</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">some_key</span><span class="p">)</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>As usual - you can use <a href="https://github.com/bbatsov/rubocop">RuboCop</a>
to identify and fix such shortfalls of your code.</p>
:ET